SA&rsquo;s bond market was firmer in late afternoon trade on Tuesday, on optimism that weak economic growth had bottomed out."After a grim 2016, growth in SA would recover more quickly than most expect, reaching 2% in 2017 and 1.7% in 2018," said Capital Economics analyst John Ashbourne.GDP contracted 0.3% in the fourth quarter, according to Statistics SA, after 0.4% growth in the third quarter.Mining and manufacturing&sbquo; which together contribute about an eighth of GDP&sbquo; were among the main factors.The economy grew 0.3% in 2016.At 3.42pm the yield on the benchmark R186 was at 8.645% from 8.67% and the yield on the R207 was at 7.655% from 7.675%.The local bond market was also following a firmer rand as US treasuries were sold off ahead of an expected US interest-rate hike next week, which could further strengthen the dollar.US bond yields surged after President Donald Trump&rsquo;s election victory, but were trading below recent peaks over the past month."The bond market seems to be more sceptical of the reflation trade under a Trump administration," Old Mutual Multi-Managers strategist Izak Odendaal said.The benchmark US 10-year bond was at 2.5079% from 2.4988%.